{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "\"Regulation Service\" OR \"Regulation Up\" OR \"Regulation Down\" participation requirements ancillary services",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "CAISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "96c1b987-58f5-45c5-92f0-9140e3a7f7b7",
        "score": 0.562487,
        "text": "The document page discusses the allocation of Ancillary Service (AS) Awards on an Energy Bid, focusing on the dispatchable capacity of a resource. It explains that portions of the Energy Bid allocated to Regulation Up and Regulation Down are ignored beyond certain limits. The exhibit illustrates how AS Awards are allocated across different segments like Regulation Down (RegDn), Non-Spin, Spin, and Regulation Up (RegUp).\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Energy Bids and Operating Reserve**: Energy Bids are necessary for dispatching Operating Reserve but not for Regulation. Regulation Up AS Awards are allocated based on the upper regulating limit or a lower derated operating limit, regardless of Energy Bids.\n\n2. **Upper Regulating Limit**: The upper portion of resource capacity is allocated to Regulation based on the Energy Bid Curve, not for dispatch. Regulation is managed by Automatic Generation Control (AGC) to maintain system frequency, considering constraints like Ramp Rate.\n\n3. **AGC Coordination**: AGC dispatches resources based on internally created prices to ensure balanced control across all resources, preventing concentration on a few.\n\n4. **Deviation from Dispatch Operating Point (DOP)**: If a resource deviates from its DOP due to AGC actions, the Real-Time Market (RTM) will adjust the resource back to its DOP. Any imbalance energy due to deviation is attributed to Regulation.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of AGC in maintaining system balance and the role of Energy Bids in resource allocation for regulation purposes.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_185.jpg",
          "page_num": 185,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a532146e-59c5-48fd-a395-c8d9f68db524",
        "score": 0.55520844,
        "text": "The document is a section from the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement Tariff, focusing on regulations related to ancillary services. It outlines the following key points:\n\n1. **Regulation Down Neutrality Adjustment**: This involves allocating the difference between the Regulation Down Reserve Cost and total revenue from all Scheduling Coordinators to each coordinator based on their obligation quantity.\n\n2. **Regulation Down Mileage Costs**: Charges for Regulation Down Mileage are calculated based on the Scheduling Coordinator\u2019s Ancillary Services Obligation percentage and the user rate for Regulation Down Mileage for each Settlement Period.\n\n3. **Regulation Up**: Charges for Regulation Up are determined by the product of the Scheduling Coordinator\u2019s hourly obligation and the user rate for Regulation Up.\n\n4. **Hourly User Rate for Regulation Up**: This rate is calculated by dividing the total Regulation Up cost by the total Net Procurement of Regulation Up by CAISO. The cost includes revenues credited to suppliers and adjustments for any unavailability of Regulation Up capacity.\n\nThe document provides detailed formulas and methodologies for calculating costs and allocations related to Regulation Down and Up services.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_343.jpg",
          "page_num": 343,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a2144460-00e9-4f8f-80fa-0c9f7a7259c8",
        "score": 0.55344707,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring \u2013 California ISO, dated July 2022, and it discusses quarterly average day-ahead ancillary service requirements. \n\n- **Figure 5.3**: Displays the average requirements for four types of services: regulation down, regulation up, spin, and non-spin from 2019 to 2021. \n\n- **Regulation Requirements**: The California ISO calculates these based on observed needs from the previous year, updating them regularly. Adjustments can be made for higher net load variability.\n\n- **2021 Observations**: \n  - Both regulation up and down requirements decreased, but regulation down saw a significant increase, averaging 684 MW (30% increase from 2020).\n  - Regulation up averaged 404 MW (4% increase from 2020).\n\n- **Hourly Profile**: Regulation down requirements were generally higher than regulation up. Regulation up was highest during mid-day and early evening, while regulation down peaked from hours 8 to 21, especially when solar power was changing.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2021/page_185.jpg",
          "page_num": 185,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "49515d9c-667f-45ab-b197-720f360a50ee",
        "score": 0.5498054,
        "text": "The document is from the California Independent System Operator Corporation and outlines requirements for submitting bids for Ancillary Services. Key points include:\n\n1. **Submission Requirements**: A submission to self-provide an Ancillary Service must meet all requirements except for price information. Scheduling Coordinators must comply with Section 8 requirements.\n\n2. **Energy Bids**: When submitting Self-Schedule Hourly Blocks for Ancillary Services in the Real-Time Market, an Energy Bid must also be submitted for the same Resource ID. If not, bid validation rules will apply.\n\n3. **Use of Bids**: If a Self-Scheduled Hourly Block is submitted, CAISO will use the Ancillary Services Bid in RTM optimization, not the associated Energy Bid for scheduling energy from non-dynamic resources.\n\n4. **Regulation Up/Down Bids**: These bids must include:\n   - The range of generating capacity for regulation within ten minutes.\n   - Bid prices for capacity reservation and mileage, stated separately for Regulation Up and Down.\n   - Contract Reference Number for Dynamic System Resources.\n\n5. **Pricing**: For self-provided Regulation Up/Down, capacity reservation is priced at $0/MWh, and mileage is $0.\n\n6. **Inter-temporal Opportunity Costs**: These can be included in bids but must be verifiable.\n\n7. **Energy Supply Bids**: Not required for Regulation bids in Day-Ahead or Real-Time Markets unless needed to maintain Regulation Down to its lower limit.\n\nThe document emphasizes compliance with specific sections and rules for bid submissions and validations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_818.jpg",
          "page_num": 818,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a31a677e-117c-47ce-aef0-f96d049e5690",
        "score": 0.54676026,
        "text": "The document is a section from the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement Electronic Tariff. It outlines the procedures and requirements for Scheduling Coordinators to self-provide Ancillary Services, specifically Regulation Up, Regulation Down, Spinning Reserve, and Non-Spinning Reserve. \n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Submissions**: Submissions for Regulation Up and Down will be rejected if the Energy Bid is outside the resource's Regulating Range. CAISO may add other services as needed.\n\n2. **Time Frame for Informing CAISO**:\n   - **Day-Ahead Schedule**: Coordinators must submit information within the timeframe in Section 30. Failure to do so results in invalid self-provision for that hour.\n   - **RTM (Real-Time Market)**: Similar requirements apply, with the timeframe in Section 30.1.\n\n3. **Information Submission**: Coordinators must submit specific information for each service as described in Section 30. For Ancillary Service Inter-SC Trades, compliance with Section 28.2 is required.\n\n4. **Acceptance Conditions**: CAISO will reject submissions that do not meet tariff requirements. Coordinators must have a current certificate of technical eligibility for the resource selected for the services.\n\nThe document emphasizes compliance with specified timeframes and conditions to ensure valid self-provision of services.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_173.jpg",
          "page_num": 173,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

